INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4300','letter','1786-03-02','New York','NY','US','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','In December, a young man, under the influence of more important advisers, made an attack in the papers, which rendered the publication of my correspondence with him expedient.','ltr_joj4300.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4301','letter','1786-03-16','New York','NY','US','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','An opinion begins to prevail, that a General Convention for revising the articles of Confederation would be expedient.','ltr_joj4301.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4302','letter','1786-06-27','Philadelphia','PA','US','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','Our affairs seem to lead to some crisis; some revolution ; something that I cannot foresee, or conjecture. I am uneasy and apprehensive ; more so than during the war.','ltr_joj4302.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4303','letter','1787-01-07','New York','NY','US','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','Shall we have a King ? Not, in my opinion, while other expedients remain untried. Might we not have a Governor-General, limited in his prerogatives and duration ?','ltr_joj4303.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4304','letter','1788-07-04','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','I congratulate you, my dear Sir, on the adoption of the Constitution by Virginia. That event has disappointed the expectation of opposition here, which nevertheless continues pertinacious.','ltr_joj4304.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4305','letter','1788-07-17','Poughkeepsie','NY','US','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Convention this moment adjourned, and I am writing in their chamber. A question being about to be put on the mode of adoption (which you have seen), we moved that the House adjourn for a month or two.','ltr_joj4305.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4308','letter','1794-09-13','London','','ENG','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Secretary\'s letter by Mr. Monroe, and the speech of the latter to the Convention, are printed; and have caused a disagreeable sensation in the public mind here, and probably in that of the Government.','ltr_joj4308.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_joj4310','letter','1796-01-26','New York','NY','US','John','Jay','','George','Washington','','individual','','For the debts, it seems to me best to take some sensible merchant, north of the Potomac, and particularly of Philadelphia, if one of acknowledged weight and character could be found willing to serve.','ltr_joj4310.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
